article.description: Dirk Nowitzki bailed Dallas out of another bad shooting night, scoring 10 of his 30 points in the fourth quarter as the Mavericks beat the Washington Wizards 92-86 Monday night.
article.headline: On ugly shooting night, Nowitzki saves Mavericks
article.linkText: Mavs not as pretty, but still find way to top Wizards
article.story:
DALLAS -- The way the Dallas Mavericks played their first 24 games, even they were starting to think little could go wrong. The last three games have provided a reality check. Dirk Nowitzki bailed Dallas out of another bad shooting night, scoring 10 of his 30 points in the fourth quarter as the Mavericks beat the Washington Wizards 92-86 Monday night. "We all know what's going on -- we've been lackadaisical, fooling ourselves a little bit,'' said reserve Walt Williams. "Everyone expects us to score 100 every night. But if we want to be an elite team, we've got to learn to grind it out like this.'' The Mavericks were averaging more than 106 points per game until scoring 80 in a win at Denver, then 81 against Utah in their first home loss of the season. They almost got stuck in the 80s again, but Washington sent them to the line in the closing minutes. The Wizards remained within six most of the game and made it 80-79 on a 3-pointer by Jerry Stackhouse, who had 28 points and tied a season-high with 10 rebounds, with 5:57 left. "I couldn't have asked for anything more,'' Washington coach Doug Collins said. "I thought if we could hit a couple of big shots, we could steal the game.'' Nowitzki answered by hitting a jumper as the shot clock expired, then put back a rebound to make it 84-79. The Wizards wouldn't get closer than that again. Washington's next basket came with 1:09 left. During the drought, Michael Jordan was called for traveling and missed a 15-footer, Stackhouse fumbled a pass out of bounds and jammed a layup attempt into the bottom of the rim, and Christian Laettner was called for three seconds. "That's frustrating,'' said Jordan, who scored 13 points on 5-of-15 shooting and had eight assists and seven rebounds in what could be his last game in Texas. "We were right there. Our defense was great, but on offense we weren't patient and took quick shots.'' Collins said the Mavericks stopped the Wizards by going back to a zone. "We played hard defensively and made the stops when we had to,'' Dallas' Steve Nash said. "Right now we're going through a little bit of a lull, and that's when our defense has to come up big.'' Nowitzki, who tied his season-high with 17 rebounds, shot just 9-of-23 and missed both his 3-pointers. His scoring was boosted by going 12-of-14 from the foul line, an indication that he's not settling for outside shots. "I missed a lot of wide-open shots early on,'' Nowitzki said. "But I just tried to be more aggressive and get to the free-throw line and then, luckily, a couple shots fell in for me.'' Nowitzki also played all 48 minutes for the second straight game, prompting Michael Finley to say: "I know what I'm getting Dirk for Christmas: a massage for his back, because he's definitely carried us.'' The Mavericks' offense was more varied than it was in the loss to Utah on Saturday. Nowitzki, Finley and Nash had all but 12 of the team's points in that game. This time, the other nine Mavs scored 32. Nash had 16 points and Finley 14. Shawn Bradley had 10 points and seven rebounds. "It's not as pretty as it was earlier, but we're still finding ways to win,'' said Nick Van Exel, who made up for a 1-of-7 shooting night with eight rebounds and six assists, including the 5,000th of his career. It came on a pick-and-roll with Nowitzki that made it 82-79. After seeing the Mavericks on one of their off nights, Jordan wasn't ready to proclaim them the team to beat in the West, despite their NBA-best record of 23-4. "They have quality players who can score,'' Jordan said. "But either way, they've got to go through L.A. or Sacramento. If they can force the other team to adjust to their style, who knows?'' Washington's Larry Hughes scored a season-high 24 points, hitting all three of his 3-point attempts. He was 8-of-11 overall.

Game notes
Jordan helped draw a season-best crowd of 20,119. ... If this was it for Jordan in Texas, he leaves having scored 2,163 points in 72 games, an average of 30 points. ... Jordan came in with the fourth-best scoring average by a Mavs opponent at 27.9 points per game in 29 meetings. ... Dallas beat Washington at home for only the third time in 11 meetings.
